<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08064e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08064e">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08064e"> 64(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lying spirit in heaven</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">There is a curious passage in the first book of Kings xxii. 19 et seq.) Jahveh, angry with Ahab, king of Israel, seeks the means to urge him to an enterprise wherein he will perish. Then &ldquo;<i>a spirit</i>&rdquo; presents himself before the Lord and offers, in order to persuade the king, to be a <i>lying spirit</i> in the mouth of his prophets, in such a manner that they will give him the fatal advice Jahveh wishes him to follow. Tis &ldquo;<i>spirit</i>&rdquo; here plays a truly diabolical part; &hellip; Nevertheless, <i>he was one of the host of heaven</i>, he is a servant of Jahveh <small> Charles Guignebert, <a name="CDEV" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CDEV"><cite title="source">&ldquo;Concerning the devil&rdquo;</cite></a>, <cite a>The Criterion</cite></a> (Oct 1923) 21-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
